# Introduction and Podcast Setup

Welcome to the Stranded Technologies podcast, where we explore how to accelerate the future. Imagine a world of abundance, longer lives, clean energy, transparent markets, robots and AI doing the toiling labor. Why don't we have those things yet? Join us as we explore the biggest problem that holds back frontier tech: overregulation. Now we have real solutions: startup cities, network states, and on-chain finance. Please find ways to support us in the show notes. Now enjoy this episode.

All right, so today is January the 13th in 2026. My guest is Jonathan Anomaly. Jonathan is a philosophy professor and now startup builder at Herasight. Herasight is building genetic tests for family planning. So we have that background in common. I also come from a background of philosophy and then started building startups. Besides that, Jonathan has become a friend over the years. He's been visiting us here in Prospera many times. And I'm always excited to talk to a brilliant friend. Besides that, I'm also excited to record the first episode for this podcast in a new podcast studio in Prospera done by Civil Studios. So this is the second ever podcast episode recorded in this studio. My first, before I had a bit of makeshift gear. So now we're doing this a bit more professionally. We have a really nice background view here. For new listeners of this show, this is Roatan in Honduras in the jurisdiction of Prospera, a startup city in a tropical paradise where we're building a kind of techno-libertarian utopia, as our critics like to say. Not entirely besides the point, I'd say, but it's a good thing.

So without further ado, Jonathan Anomaly, welcome back to the Promised Land.

The Promised Land, very grandiose, but I do love it here. And as you can see from the background, if you're tuning in, it is a beautiful place to live. It's a very beautiful place. Thanks for having me.

# Transition from Philosophy to Startups

Jonathan, maybe you can tell us a bit about your background, but specifically about the transition from a philosopher that's turning to do startups. In what ways does philosophy help or not help you do a startup or build a company?

Yeah, I'm not sure philosophy helped me as much as economics and actually not theoretical economics. So of course I taught bits of classes, bits of price theory, kind of history of economic thought along with philosophy. You know, taught in a PPE program as you studied in philosophy, politics, economics. So but I do think there are a few relevant ideas and interesting ideas from economics. I mean, one is especially libertarians tend to believe they could be wrong sometimes, but they tend to believe that when there's a kind of market failure, there's going to also be a new market that might open up to solve it.

Of course, classically, when there's a market failure, people think, well, politicians need to do something. And libertarians like you tend to say, well, hold on a second here. Compared to what? What is the thing that they do going to look like versus some market solution? And in this case, I'm thinking about arbitraging certain kinds of taboos and what you might call political correctness. That's an old term now. But as we know, academia in the entire West, really, in the United States, but also in England, Canada, New Zealand, it's all going in the same direction ideologically. And I'm not making a strong point here about Democrats or Republicans or Labour or conservative, but it's easy to understand that when one party or one ideology captures any institution, it's going to get corrupted. The research will essentially be there to propagate the foundational assumptions of that institution and so on.

And I suppose when the topic is chemistry, there's going to be some immunity to it. Although actually, when the topic is biology and not sociology or philosophy, it's not necessarily immune because we can think of Lysenkoism in the Soviet Union. I mean, they basically rejected Darwinian evolution 50 to 70 years after Darwin lived. Why? Because the new Soviet man was going to be more altruistic and less competitive in the struggle for existence. So other kinds of disciplines can get corrupted too. But philosophy really has been corrupted, and especially when we're studying moral and political philosophy.

So what that is saying is essentially, look, you've got these institutions. We both trained in them to some extent. I was a professor. I wrote articles. I taught perfectly good classes. I did my part. And instead of getting rewarded at the end of the day, I got chased out with pitchforks. Now not literally, I didn't get thrown out of my position but you know people started noticing you have the wrong opinions about certain topics. And it was never the students actually. Rarely the students I should say tended to get you know reasonably good evaluations and so on. But you get these rogue characters in the university that would have extremely strong ideological views. And their job was to purge the institution of impurity.

And back to the economics point, when you have an idea that is either true or very likely to be true that you have some strong justification for and you express it publicly, if you're in the wrong institution you're in the church so to speak, the cathedral, and you're a heretic but you're expressing true heresies. If you have a market economy there's going to tend to open up other opportunities. And you've seen this with respect to startup societies, but my big idea, the idea that got me in a bit of trouble, is that genetics matter in explaining things like personality, life outcome, health, intelligence, all of these things. It's fairly obvious to anyone who's ever had kids or just looked at the world on its own terms. But specifically, when we understand genetics, parents are going to want to use that understanding to guide the reproductive choices.

To some extent, people do it already. They test their embryos, for example, for single gene disorders. People who sometimes who are well into pregnancy, I'm not advocating abortion or anything, but they will selectively abort if there's a Down syndrome diagnosis and that sort of thing. And I just thought, look, the science of heredity is advancing rapidly. We can already do a lot. I was thinking five years ago with polygenic risk scores for [[embryo selection]]. I'd written a book on this topic and companies are starting to do this. And so it was a natural transition for me to leave. I'll call it the public sector as a private university. But if it wasn't propped up by government money, I wouldn't call it the public sector. I left the public sector for the private sector. And now, yeah, I'm part of a company called Herasight after the goddess Hera. And we provide at some price the thing that the market wants. Whatever the clergy wants in the corrupt institution that we're calling the cathedral doesn't really matter that much. Parents want the best for their children. And so we're getting alternative forms of education. On the one hand I live in Austin and seeing educational startups everywhere, which is great. And on the other hand, the ability to start a company that provides the kind of service that I was essentially nudged out of academia for talking about. So, yeah.

# Reflections on Academia Versus Startups

Yeah, and wondering, also reflecting back on academia, my journey was slightly similar but also slightly different. I kind of dropped out of it because I found it impractical, not because I found it ideologically too conformist, which was a bit of luck because I've been in institutions that had been not too ideological. Right, so my philosophy and economics program, the founders were left-leaning people that had us read Hayek and Milton Friedman like you had a very rational, logical positivism bent. And that was kind of their one thing: look at the arguments on their merit just how you, very German by the way, logical positivist, very rational, although that was like almost the only logical positivism department in Germany. Interesting like they were very radical in okay everything else was continental philosophy. And right, yeah so I didn't experience that myself but I found okay there is just no mechanism for these true ideas to have any meaningful or practical impact. And that's why I joined startups.

So looking back, how would you kind of reflect on the difference between finding unpopular ideas or truths in academia versus startups and what difference that makes?

Yeah, I mean, the obvious answer is where there's demand, supply can emerge, it's going to be more free to emerge. But in the case of just to take what we're doing, I mean, there are many examples we can think of that are illegal. Of course, they're drugs people want to try that they can't anywhere except maybe in Prospera. So some of this depends on the luck of what state you're born into and whether you can move. I'm lucky that in the United States, actually, again, what we're doing is just to put it on the table. We're doing embryo selection. And women who do IVF can select between embryos using polygenic scores, which gauge the likelihood that they'll develop a certain disease, or we can even measure things like IQ and height. Yes, it's not all genetic, but we can understand a fair amount about the genetics of it.

And height. Yes, it's not all genetic, but we can understand a fair amount about the genetics of it. So in the US, it's completely legal. In Europe, it's almost completely illegal, as so many things are. And in the rest of the world, it's either a gray market or it's a confused market. I got lucky and, you know, there's a fairly straightforward market. So my founders are actually European. But, you know, we have these loopholes where you can start a business in Delaware and take advantage of the tax status and so on. Similarly, Prospera is going even farther and you can arbitrage some of the insane rules of Delaware. But yeah, the natural thing is if you have a big idea for which you believe there's some demand, well, you're going to move into the field to supply it. And in this case, as with so many people, sure, some are motivated by pure monetary incentives, but I take it that you and I are not. Not that we're indifferent to money or power or whatever motivates people, but some ideas are really providing a lot of value to humanity. And I'm willing to take a huge salary cut in order to promote ideas that I think are helpful for the world, for specific people in the world.

It sounds that when you say good for the world or good for humanity, a lot of people, you know, maybe they can dismiss that. Oh, good, according to you and your ideology. Maybe, but actually, like, I do think reducing disease is other things equal good. It's better to have a well-functioning immune system, you know, a brain that works properly rather than has schizophrenic hallucinations against your will, you know, whenever you don't want to have those hallucinations. And if we can actually provide a service that allows parents with a family history of disease. And let's get specific. You know, I was talking about a good society or humanity getting better. I mean, schizophrenia. I mean, having an autoimmune disorder that's crippling. I mean, having a single gene disorder that results in your own death before you're born in the womb. Reducing these things is a serious business. I mean, and this is very good for future people and for the parents that want to conceive.

You may be healthy in the audience. You may have a high IQ. You may have all these advantages. Great right. But what the universities were essentially saying to me is you evil for talking about and defending the provision of these services to people who don't have those advantages. And maybe I'll go further and provide a little cynical commentary on this right. It's always the smartest people at the best universities who say that things like intelligence isn't real and it's definitely not genetic or who say what you're doing by providing individual parents information that they find useful, that's eugenics, you're evil, we're going to chase you out of town. And it's like well we can turn the tables and say first of all isn't you trying to use the force of the state to prevent people from having this information a kind of coerced eugenics and a kind of paternalism that is, it's the kind of thing that you can afford as the rich, the healthy, the smart precisely because you're in that position. You like to talk about oppression and oppressed and privilege and so on but you are the ultimate privileged class, you know, you professors in the academy who then want to denounce people for talking about the kinds of things that will really benefit other people outside of the academy. So that's a bit of a tirade, but I feel pretty strongly this is exactly why free societies are important. They give individuals exit options when they're expressing unpopular ideas that are probably true. And they allow people on the other end to demand the provision of goods that they consider good for themselves, their family, that probably are good for themselves and their family, but which would be punished or made illegal in a kind of tyrannical society.

Yeah. I have a lot more to say about the exit part, but I'm really glad you mentioned that. I like working backwards from an idea that I care about to how could we implement this in the real world, right? So what I find compelling as an analogy is when Friedrich Hayek talked about private banking, right? And denationalization of money. And that was several decades before Bitcoin, right? So the idea was there, like we knew private banking existed before. We had some insights into how it could work and people have been working kind of on the cypherpunk fringes on that for a bit until there like a big moment and a technological shift that makes it possible and makes it practical right so i think and i think many of these things i think George Mason University and their professors are very often trailing some of these very important ideas right sort of Robin Hanson with prediction markets yep. Um or in my case, um, Alex Tabarrok and private certifiers instead of a monopoly regulator like the FDA.

So I think there's a very big value in thinking about these ideas. But I think the real lack is, or where the real time delay is, people are going out there and building companies around some of these ideas and proving that it can work and sort of give these benefits into people's hands and building technology that can scale it and make it accessible for more people.

Good. Yeah. I really like that analysis. And I know you've had basically half of the George Mason economics department here. And I'm about to see some of those guys next week in Puerto Rico, too. All of my appreciation for that. Yes. So we appreciate. Yeah. All of them have had some big ideas. And of course, this Hayek idea. So there are kind of markets waiting to happen, but someone has to create them. I mean, the classic example is the kind of iPhone or the iPod, I guess, which doesn't exist anymore because it's all been put into a single phone. But, you know, there's some risk in creating a product. You think that people will want it, but you don't know until you create it or you create a good version of it. And that requires this sort of competition and freedom to actually do something like that. So, yeah, much appreciation to them.

I want to also mention, we were talking about earlier, this concept from another George Mason economist. Sometimes I call him the Mason autists, Bryan Caplan. And that's this idea of rational irrationality. And he actually invents this in contrast to a concept implicit in Hayek and developed by Anthony Downs. And that's the idea of rational ignorance. So I could go on forever about it. I'll be concise. I think that's actually a very important concept as an entrepreneur, because you have sort of the new world in mind that is in your mind more rational and it is in some way, sort of the denationalization of money, the privatized certifiers and whatever, and the availability of genetic screening for parents. Like we thought it through and that new world makes sense. And the real world right now is irrational. It doesn't make sense. Right. But it is rational for people to distrust these new ideas.

Yeah, that's a good point. Yeah, it's good. Okay. So there's a couple layers here. I was thinking more in terms of in the public sector where there's no direct price on holding false beliefs. And in fact, you could be rewarded precisely because your beliefs are out of touch with reality. In the ideological realm, and I'll say why, we get rational irrationality, but also to some extent with new technologies, we get it. So here's the distinction. Again, implicit in Hayek, developed by Downs, Nobel Prize winning economist in public choice. You know, they're asking, why is it in a democratic society specifically, do people are people ignorant about so many things actually a democratic even market society. And Hayek you know he looks around in the 1948 essay um and he's asking well yeah it's kind of interesting like the more the more products there are that we can benefit from and that we require for daily life like we're in the studio I don't really know exactly how the cameras work I have a vague idea how they work we have a microwave that we're using to heat up our coffee whatever the case is actually there's this kind of interesting graph where it's like as prosperity goes up so too does the the quantity of things that you can't know anything about yeah the famous quotes like that the world is expanding according to the operations humanity can perform without thinking about them without needing to understand them exactly yeah that's right and so we get rational ignorance and that's actually rational in the economic sense. And it's actually morally good in the sense that if you wasted all of your time getting up in the morning, trying to understand everything, you'd be misusing your talents and you'd be doing yourself and everyone else a disservice. So rational ignorance makes sense in a complex society and rational ignorance about politics makes a lot of sense because your vote has very little impact on an overall aggregation you know you just do the math people like to moralize this stuff but do the math you see that pretty quickly but your investment to yourself is real and so people are rational ignorant about politics. Caplan comes along and he says no no it's much worse than that and he's of course right he says people have very strong beliefs and so people are rationally ignorant about politics. Caplan comes along and he says, and so people are rationally ignorant about politics. Caplan comes along and he says, oh no, it's much worse than that. And he's of course right. He says people have very strong beliefs about politics, often that they not only can't justify, but are completely at odds with reality and it's rewarded rather than punished in politics. Why? Politics and morality, as Jonathan Haidt has argued, are really about binding people together in communities. And this old part of our brain activates to figure out who's us and who's them. So us are, it's defined really as the set of people who share a bunch of either a political ideology, a religious ideology, political principles, in a way that makes perfect sense. As kind of tribal creatures, we evolve to share communities. You'd better know what the rules are, who the right people are, who the heretics are, etc. But here we are in these mass societies with hundreds of millions of people who are diverse in a thousand ways, and political ideologies evolve to sort of economize on information, tell us who to vote for, etc., and then manipulate us. And to really get us to the polls, they have to make these extreme emotional appeals, you know, to sort of say, no, no, the enemy really wants to destroy everything about your way of life. But we, we're going to save, we're going to give you meaning, we're going to give you everything that you want. And all of this makes sense. This is just people responding to the incentives of a mass democracy. But it also means there is hysteria, wildly false beliefs being propagated by the media, by universities, and absorbed by individuals who are not really completely at fault for it. They're following the incentives in a way.

Now, putting that all together, thinking about how do you not only reduce rational irrationality, but get people to do what in a way is in their interest anyway in this kind of insane world with these incentives we laid out. Again, by having a market, a true market where they can eventually test out what it is they want, try out different things and then buy the thing that looks most plausible that they want that actually helps reduce rational irrationality so just to finish you had mentioned any new product whether it be this product right. Come live in Prospera or come start your business here or embryo selection using [[polygenic scores]]. The rational move actually, and I think it's perfectly reasonable is skepticism, um, until you've proven that this works. And so, I mean, the interesting thing here is that it's just a lot faster and more efficient and has better feedback mechanisms in a market to show that it does work because people really care just to use our example because it's of course closer to my knowledge base you know we have at Herasight no marketing team at all it doesn't exist we haven't marketed we've tweeted some things we've put our papers on our website and gone on some podcasts. I suppose we'll do marketing eventually. But by contrast, there are other companies doing this where they do almost no science at all and they do a lot of marketing. And the interesting thing has been a lot of bright people in Silicon Valley. This is not a brag. It's just a sociological fact that I've found very interesting, have found a way to figure out, okay, if you really want to have the best polygenic scores go to the team that does the best science and they've found their way to us with no marketing I'm not saying you know in general therefore you shouldn't market products or something like that what I'm saying is it's interesting because you can compete with something different than in politics exactly politics you have to counter with the same kind of propaganda yeah propaganda is what works but in in a market basically if you provide what ultimately people can see as being worth their while, you're going to tend to get rewarded.

