Yeah I've been thinking about this question a lot obviously like we reading the same books we thinking about the same thing I think one thing to notice is all right if you set yourself up as like a public intellectual or as a thinker or a salesman for ideas that no longer works right you know you can still have like some vestiges or bastions of rationality you know like Scott Alexander Bay Area rationalist but even that can be subverted then by like the AI doom stuff right i guess George Mason University still stands right but the lesson from that is that that can always be subverted right and when you are subject to like the incentives of attention and media well then your path is that of a Jordan Peterson right or whatever like where you start like very thoughtful and then you kind of degenerate into sort of the attention seeking modes of operation I think it's just important to notice that incentive and why is that and I think it's largely because we have these very large political blocks and tribes right so we're dividing the country into two main tribes and there's loads of benefits tied to being in one tribe or the other so if you are becoming you can't become part of that machinery right you need an exit and I think the great thing is about the world we live in now that that exit that we're building as entrepreneurs has two advantages one is we can actually protect ourselves sort of when I think about Vitalik's defensive accelerationism like we have more countries to go to we have communities in other places that get us that get tech that get crypto that gets the kind of things we care about on many different levels we have competing jurisdictions right so prospera is not super new in the sense that for the last like 30 40 years like the Sovereign Individual already observed that that's starting with rich people always does right that they already have more options in mobility and also because of technology and the internet and now especially crypto it's just much harder for government to seize their wealth right so one is that you really setting yourself up defensively to not be captured by sort of that large apparatus and the other is that exit that you do especially as someone who built something is contributive right so what you're doing is still benefiting the people from your society you're not like a even if you move from like the United States to Prospera whatever you're still contributing and developing good products for people in America or the United States or you can stay faithful to sort of the American values or ideals that you cherish that might not entirely look like you want them to look right now, but you can still realize that vision elsewhere, right? Sort of the idea can be decentralized and it can be continued in Prospera and to some degree in Dubai and Singapore and other places, right? So I think there's actually very strong fuel kind of for the flame of liberty to kind of shine, right? By sort of decentralizing and, you know, It doesn't necessarily mean you have to say goodbye forever to the United States or never be there or go to San Francisco to raise funds for your startup or whatever, right?

Yeah, yeah, I like that point. And I wanted to kind of touch on one of those things in particular. At the beginning, you mentioned the kind of two tribes or two parties. And it's maybe no coincidence that in most democracies, even the ones that have multiple parties and so on, you know, you tend to get convergence towards splitting the world into two. And it's just the easiest way of doing things. Well, especially when a majority is what you need, you know, a majority of votes, a majority of people, you know, putting their thumbs up, whatever the thing is. And, you know, there's a paper I mentioned, Bryan Caplan's idea of rational irrationality. He published a paper on this in, I believe, 1999, Rational Irrationality Versus Rational Ignorance. His friend, Michael Huemer, who's a philosopher, and I know, you know, Michael as well, he wrote a nice paper, we actually published it in our PPE Oxford anthology in 2015, called Why People Are Irrational About Politics. And, and the reason I mentioned that essay is, you know, he like Hayek and Downs that he kind of recognizes, you know, there's this gravity toward, creating two ideologies. And it's not totally out of touch with reality in the sense that when we think about left and right, there are some generalizations we could make. Okay the left cares more about equality than the right That true especially equal outcomes The right is more willing to acknowledge hierarchies and things And some of those are probably good, right? If you don't have a CEO of a company, it's probably not going to work. There are hierarchies and some people are smarter than others and others are more diligent or more morally responsible, but not as smart and they all have their roles. And on the right, you're more likely to recognize that. But the truth is when you watch the way leftists behave, they know that i mean come on when you implement Marxism has it ever been egalitarianism egalitarian on any level not at all right so the truth is it's just a way of it makes sense as a sociological phenomenon to have these like permanent tribes competing in a large kind of democratic society it makes sense given the incentives that parties and politicians have but i just want to stress you know this is the Huemer point and sorry to be you know giving the freshman 101 lecture or whatever but i just think it was such a great insight for me i didn't have it till i was like 35 or something that this trap is something we all fall into and it's it's created by incentives that you yourself are probably unaware of i don't mean you nick but a lot of people are and and it's kind of entropy we're we're always going to be drawn back into this as long as we buy into the system and we have this tendency to say yeah yeah this these are my people this is my party and you're going to tend to conform your beliefs your your view of reality uh with one of those and i just think it's a permanent danger and again this is why well i'm on vacation right now i'm here for a few days i'm on route to Puerto Rico to give some talks and stuff but I wanted to come here to kind of clear the mind do some work just live in a place that was free and I'll say one more thing, because this is funny. I tell people I moved to Ecuador in 2021 to work briefly with the president's main counselor. And I moved to Ecuador to reclaim my freedom because the United States was under a kind of tyrannical regime. And it's like when I'm in Singapore, I'm joking. I'm going back to Honduras to safety. Yes, exactly. Yeah, exactly. So or, you know, San Salvador. I go to El Salvador a couple of times a year. I take surf trips, you know, I go with my family or friends and I can choose where and I want to go. The streets are clean I feel freedom etc And so anyway it just a good reminder Places like this are important if nothing else because it gives you not just an out in terms of selling products Yeah, that's all really cool. But just ideologically to be in a place where actually there are very few incentives to conform your views to one of these two stupid parties.

Yeah, I think if you follow my two things, I have to say one is the idea that I think you do the biggest leverage for realizing kind of a more decentralized world that I've talked about is to remove the double taxation in the United States because Americans are the have the most libertarians in the world the most entrepreneurs in the world on a per capita basis although you know Singapore might compete or Norway or whatever and also the kinds of people who would want to leave to build something somewhere else are also disproportionately more likely to actually buy into the American ideal right so I think that would decentralize America a lot by you know um but anyway that's a very pet you gotta whisper in the right person's ear while there's well there's time in the Trump administration yeah exactly and yeah the other thought was um the I think what matters is the rules by which um how powerful can the leaders of these political camps become right so in the current world or in the world where most of the wealth was created like in physical space in factories whatever these were easy to seize right so unions quickly seized them and those were possible to be captured by governments for big voting blocs right so we see a world with very large and powerful governments almost like as a function of technology right that's a bit the Sovereign Individual thesis right so and that makes us relatively centralized or decentralize more, right? So versus like the Colt as the equalizer, right? So the Colt and a small handgun gives a person that's in a wheelchair similar protection to a person that's not, that's perfectly healthy and would be physically strong enough to be sort of a knight in an armor or with a sword would have struck down like multiple weaker people without a handgun otherwise. So I think the technology and sense of technology in that sense really matters. So we can still play our tribal games as long as the tribes don't have the power to like destroy each other and destroy the whole world in the process Right So and you know you see sort of healthy competition delegated to things like sports where you know, hooligans are very tribal and they beat each other up once in a while. Right. Yeah. But you know, they don't use that new weapons for that. And they don't have to power to like literally destroy. They're not waging mass war. Yeah. Destroying the other tribe. Yeah, that's right. Yeah. Something you said that also struck me as interesting is we could think of exit, exit abilities as on a par with owning a pistol. I, I always to, to keep my Spanish up to date, you know, I speak to Cubans and Venezuelans who are driving taxis and in Florida and Texas, where I spend a lot of time and, and, you know, they're, they always pretty much all of them have the same view, which is, of course we oppose the government. We want it to collapse, but this is why they disarm us. Right. And this is why they make it, they make it difficult for us to do anything and one way of disarming your government a corrupt tyrannical government is precisely by having some structural mechanism to be able to leave physically monetarily whatever so on the one hand you've mentioned of course Bitcoin the ability to physically leave or this this idea of just abolishing this horrible tax that the American government imposes I had to do this when I moved to Ecuador for for the year I had to pay double taxes and just by if we could somehow get rid of that. Of course, there are incentives for governments to keep that for precisely that reason. But this is maybe a good lesson for apart from startup societies, apart from the kind of thing that you're doing, thinking about how to how to pass through these simple structural reforms that actually have these hidden benefits that politicians aren't going to be rethinking about that much. They're thinking about, you know, reelection in the short term and how do I reward certain people in exchange for votes and money and that sort of thing but God if you could just structurally change the tax system a little bit it would yeah benefit people greatly and punish politicians in ways they might not fully understand yeah I have some more pet peeves on how to do that yeah but um one conversation I want to have with you is the more practical side of building a company around an unpopular but good idea right so the idea of like genetic testing or screening especially for controversial areas like IQ or whatever, you had to think what is kind of your PR and go-to-market strategy, right? Can you talk a bit about that and sort of generalize that a bit as advice for other entrepreneurs who are thinking about doing or already doing something similar?

Yeah, sure. A lot of these things, you know, they're embodied in practice rather than explicitly articulated, you know, sort of Hayekian point. But I, you know, whether I was a professor or now kind of a spokesperson for Herasight, I, nobody tells the truth all the time. Obviously, you omit certain things. I mean, if your wife asks you how good she looks in the dress or whatever, the correct answer isn't always the truth. We all we all do that. But I try. I try. Maybe don't succeed to be as honest as I can, especially about things that matter and the thing that I'm talking about. So with genetic testing and so on. One interesting strategy that has backfired for some people in this space, I'm not going to name names, but I know, of course, we all know each other in this space of genetic testing. It's very small. And I know that none of them oppose IQ testing and all of them think that IQ is something worth offering people, either because they want it or because the founders believe in it and so on. But they were afraid to do it they're afraid of getting criticized by the media now we took some arrows by the media maybe not as bad as it would have been five years ago but we've taken some but I tend to be just as honest and open about this as possible which is well look there actually are real benefits to to biological intelligence in fact my talk next week in Puerto Rico is why biological intelligence still matters in a world of artificial intelligence right the ability to resist manipulation, to succumb to common statistical fallacies. I mean, intelligence does help you. It doesn't guarantee it, right? Intelligence plus ideology is a really dangerous mix. But actually, intelligence at least is one enabling condition among others, including living in a virtuous culture, being raised by parents that emphasize certain virtues, schools, etc. So I think if you frame certain issues in an honest and open way, I mean, I know people are going to disagree with me on that still some people still don't think selecting for intelligence is good for whatever reason but they going to realize like correctly i not advocating that we going to force people to do this i not an IQ maximizer I actually constantly say I think virtue matters more than intelligence I think creativity matters at least as much. Personality matters. All these things matter. And, you know, in the context of selection, embryo selection in particular, as I like to say, the most important decision you can make is selecting your partner. And then people make various priorities about diseases and so on, and then look at things like intelligence. And that makes sense.

So when you, okay, back to the marketing point, since that was the question. When you do interviews about these things and we're all over the press now, it's true, like part of the time, I think you should ignore press inquiries. There's no doubt when people are completely hostile and not open to reason, the best thing to do is ignore them, not give them fuel, not give them what they want, which is a reaction. But even if a lot of journalists and a lot of people are against what you're doing or they think they are, they often don't fully realize why they are. They can't articulate it. And if you can draw them out to articulate their worries, is it about inequality? Well, what kinds of inequality are you worried about, right? Is it financial or genetic inequality? And do you think these inequalities might be compensated in the future as the price goes down and the quality goes up and future people who otherwise would have horrible diseases don't have them in the future. Is that what you're worried about? Are you worried about the state having control? Well, wait a minute. Isn't your position that the state should have more control because what we're doing is bad because we're giving information to parents? Really kind of testing them out and not mocking them, really being quite open. Actually, yesterday I was on Louise Perry's show. She's very much a conservative, but not a religious conservative. And I debated someone with the Heritage Foundation. And I thought it was, we all walked away just thinking that's what a debate should look like. We laid out the areas we disagree on. And we articulated what we agreed on. And we walked away just thinking, okay, now people will make up their own minds. And I think the answer to your question then is, be as clear as possible about what your marketing. Don't try to take the audience that is completely hostile to what you're doing and saying oh yeah we going to convince them to like it Maybe they will in the long run but that probably a bad idea And actually you should be a bit open to the media They are sometimes convincible You not going to change their ideology but you know you can you can I'll give you a hint. You can, you can drop certain lines in ways that are almost guaranteed to be printed, which you can use against the journalist, against their intention. So for example, I'll give you a concrete case. I've learned it's almost never a good idea to do interviews that can be edited, right? Deceptive editing is very real. I was interviewed, for example, by CBS News, by actually a reasonably friendly guy. I actually like him a lot. It went on for well over two hours, and the questions got a bit more hostile in the end, kind of warmed up, et cetera. And I don't think he had any hand in editing the final tape. I think the CBS editors did. Well, they have their own agenda, right? And so they cut down two and a half hours to about 18 seconds. And it was cut in such a way that it was trying to embarrass me. Like, you know, he had asked a question to me for which I gave an eight minute answer. You know, here are the three different answers I have. I had thought these things through. I'd written a book on this topic. But instead, what they did is they panned over to me, kind of nervously reaching for my water bottle and taking a sip. Well, that was actually done some minutes later. You know, what they were trying to convey is, oh, this guy doesn't have a good answer and he's super nervous about this question. So my advice is don't do those live interviews or sorry, do live interviews. That's okay. As long as they're not going to be cut. Don't do recorded interviews, especially from hostile media. Podcasts are okay because you get to give the full answer and they're not going to edit it. If you do agree to give interviews that are later cut, you should film them and you should ask them ahead of time, is it okay to film them in advance so that you could then publicize the way in which they deceptively edited? And when there is some media, some journalists that you're uncertain about, ask for the questions in print and you have zero obligation morally or legally to answer all of their questions or to answer them in the ways they want you to answer them, right? So just ignore questions. And in some cases, they'll ask three, and you give one answer that ties them together in ways that benefit you. Now, I hate to be a kind of Machiavellian about this. That not my general attitude I started off by saying I try to be as honest as possible And I think you should Nevertheless you can recognize that journalists are not necessarily your friends and they may be quite hostile. And so that these are some tricks that you can use. So if they're looking for quotes, make sure that, again, it's better to answer in print than in person sometimes. And when that's true, answer in such a way that you, you know, one of those sentences taken out of context doesn't look especially bad because they will do that if you allow them to so so yeah be careful with pre-recorded interviews if you do them at all record them at the same time so you could then later go on social media to show they deceptively edited don't answer extremely hostile journalists unless they're going to print something that's false and libelous in which case i would actually go through lawyers to answer them and we've done that. And then do be open actually to people who disagree with you because some journalists are open to speaking and you can speak off the record first, then speak on the record on your terms. Right. So a lot of people don't know these things going in, but that's my general advice. And then finally, I mean, maybe it'll differ across sectors, but, you know, we, we saw it as the most appropriate thing to build the best scientifically justifiable product that we could. So hire the best scientists first. That both gives you a solid product, competitive advantage, a competitive advantage in the market and signals to people this is a serious company. You've got people who are widely recognized as the leading authority in their field. Then do the marketing. Don't do the opposite. So there are companies that go marketing first and I get it. You should have a slick website. But, you know, if you're a serious person that wants to add value to the world and make money by adding value, not by manipulation, then be serious about it. Be willing to hire the best first. Build that product while in stealth or while you're trying things out. Then get the marketing team.

Yeah, I was looking for something also very specific with what you did was, OK, you wanted to remember our conversation, have the first like happy customers, for example. Yeah right because happy customers are your best advocates it's very hard to argue with happy healthy happy parents and healthy newborn babies or in our case like patients that have been treated like with diseases and are now healthy right so our case like patients that have been treated like with diseases and are now healthy right so this is also seen this as a strategy very explicitly by people who do this very successfully like Uber for example had um basically New Yorkers vote um to benefit Uber right it was not like a big favor that could ask but like a very small sort of Bill de Blasio button they had in the to advocate users on their behalf. So I think making users and the benefits you add to them part of your strategy is a thing.

I love that point because actually we gave discounts early on to customers for testimonials, but it's not an exchange for testimonials exactly. So we made clear in the contracts, if you're not happy with the product, you could say bad things, you could say nothing, you could do whatever you want. We're just convinced that you are going to be happy. Yeah and if you are happy then you know go ahead and give us a video testimonial and I've seen and you know that's just a way of rewarding people it's it's it's not a bribe it's to say like most people want their privacy they don't want to do a testimonial under their real name and have you you know put their video out or have journalists you know recycle it but if you're willing to take this this little risk for yourself you know what will reward you but we're not going to put you in a position where you feel like you have to. We're actually, we've even put in some contracts early days. I mean, it's going to change when we grow, but like, actually the price for you is going to be nothing if you aren't happy with the service. And we did that two or three times. And in the end, they did pay us either in the form of money or testimonials or referrals or whatever. And it's just a way of saying, yeah, if you really believe in these things, like have your customer be part of the advertising. They're your best ally.

I would also say you need to be able to show that you can convince thoughtful people. So a general heuristic for good ideas is thoughtful people can agree to it if given the arguments and the facts, regardless of their political orientation or ideology. So if you have something that a lot of people agree on that out of like one political tribe, that's an indication, well, maybe it's not necessarily thoughtful people that agree with that even though you have like lots of followers for your ideas or whatever But in like in the cases also the ones that we work on right where it about like real scientific proof like does it work or doesn't it you need to be able you show that you can convince thoughtful people like you're not some like edgelord out there that's like you know it's so important to be contrarian have these all these unpopular ideas no if it is a good idea then you can convince thoughtful people, even though they weren't convinced before. Right. I like that point. And it's fairly obvious, like in our case, I can't generalize to every company, but we did go to the kind of Bay Area rationalists and some of these communities first or people who, since we're testing for disease, people who we know are looking to reduce disease. Maybe they've been in the news. They had a kid with some severe genetic disorder. Well, probably if they want a second kid, they're going to want to use our service. That's also pronatalists and people like that. Pronatalists are going to be the kind of people who are on the one hand, weird, like rationalists tend to be weird people, you know, and I don't mean that in a derogatory way. They're just unusual, neuroatypical and that sort of thing. And like, you know, what are you trying to do early on? You're trying to make sure your product works, there's demand for it, you get feedback on it. And it's always going to be weird people who want to start with your product first, but also people who know that, okay, let's say I'm a pronatalist. I want to have a bunch of kids. I'm going through IVF anyway, for whatever reason, it's fairly natural that I'm going to want to test those kids genetically or whatever. So I think that's right. You can find these kinds of markets first where it's clear there will be demand. It's non-ideological demand. Then you can worry later, like after you've proven a good fit, how do we market it to other people? And once you've got a base of users who are fanatically, you know, endorsing what you're doing, so to speak, it's just going to be a lot easier to do that.

# Polygenic Screening Technology and Market Strategy

Let me add one more thing. I've been, I've been talking about this more and more, but I think it's super important. And it actually brings together the point that we just made together because you really made the point, I expanded on it, but also the point at the beginning about taboos and academia and so on, and how arbitrage those taboos. I highly recommend either the book or the essay with the same name by Timur Kuran, Private Truths, Public Lies, The Social Consequences of Preference Falsification. It always gonna be it should have been written a lot sooner it should have been written by Aristotle I don't know why it took so long to write but but it's a great book and the the examples are interesting and the thesis is interesting and the point that I want to make about it is when there is a product that you develop again the kind of boring one but still it changed the world is the iPod which became the iPhone etc startup societies genetic testing whatever. There are all kinds of taboos. In this case, with genetic testing, the taboo is clear. It's World War II. It's just an overreaction, albeit justifiable maybe to some extent at the beginning, to this idea that it's just the race is the only thing that matters. And what is the race? It's a set of genes and sort of Deutschland, Uber Alles, whatever. So there's this overreaction to whatever it is that was going on in the 1930s. So we're just going to do the opposite, right? I don't know why Hitler was a vegetarian so we're going to eat as much meat as possible or something that's the logic it's kind of stupid but rather than isolating the things that were wrong and not doing those but what happens is i mean maybe for understandable Darwinian reasons you know we're a social animal speaking of Darwin or of Aristotle man is a social political animal our brains run on the software of ideology the ideology we absorb after World War II in the West not in Singapore, not in China or India is the blank slate theory of human nature it's wrong and it's evil to give genetic explanations of anything or to manipulate genes which in a way genetic selection is doing it's not editing but it's choosing which genetic endowment should live and which one shouldn't and so on in in this society where there are these taboos each of us of course you know privately understands that personality intelligence health all of these things are to more or less degree heritable but we also recognize that there's this public taboo associated with it and it's the worst in academia of course and as Timur Kuran says in this in this great book and his thesis is look what happens at the end stages of an ideology as it's about to crumble and he's thinking of communism in Eastern Germany, but other examples too, is we get this sense by ordinary people and especially elites, okay, I know this doesn't work. I think I know, or I believe that you know it doesn't work but I don't know that you know that I know it doesn't work You know and there's this this problem of of figuring things out And as soon as we break this this this um it's called pluralistic ignorance. Like, I don't know what you know about me and you don't know what I know about you when we break that. And the internet really helps break that and other decentralized technologies and people can speak freely about these things. What happens is suddenly, you know, the ideology is exposed and everyone knows it's false and everyone knows it's self-destructive and the elites tend to start by publicly announcing it, some of them bravely at first and others not so bravely following. And then suddenly you go from communism as the dogma one year to communism as the most evil thing in the world the following year. And so you see eastern Germany being far more right-wing than than west Germany precisely because of that they've experienced this this evil and wrong ideology and so I want to bring that together to just say with genetic testing for example what happens is at first a few people who just don't care about social norms the the weirdo rationalist so to speak and again I use that term you know favorably not unfavorably they kind of do it and they announce it and and a few other elites will kind of step up and and in five or ten years if we're back here again doing this podcast I suspect we're going to see a reversal a kind of preference cascade whereby large numbers of people when all not only privately believe the things that they already do but publicly endorse them and when you look around the world we have good polling data on this the differences between the West and the East, the East simply doesn't have the taboos about the genetics of mental traits and personality traits that we do. They don't draw the distinction between selecting against disease and selecting in favor of mental traits or aesthetic traits. Privately, of course, privately, of course, we make these distinctions. People want to see beautiful actors. They say things like, well, my kid is so smart, he got into this honors program. Of course they know intelligence is real and beauty is real and these things are shaped by genes, but they just know they're not allowed to let themselves believe it or say it in the context of the reproductive realm. And here I'm going to plug Marx. Marx was right about this thing. When you introduce new technology into the world, you create new incentives that makes it more likely. So let's say a backdrop of free speech to some extent, and then new incentives created by a new technology. And suddenly you put a price on having false beliefs. And that price for some is less easy to pay because my kid, I don't want him to have a genetic disease or my kid, I want him to have certain advantages. I start saying it publicly. Others do too. Let's say there's some ability to speak freely, et cetera. And then suddenly what you're going to get is a preference cascade where the fall of, or as I like to say, the breaking of the blank slate may end up mirroring the fall of communism in the East.

Yeah. So to close it off, can you apply that insight sort of that there are things people want, but are afraid to ask, um, also to your business and maybe talk to our listeners a bit about what they could get from the product, right? Because I think many of our listeners would be interested. Um, so maybe close off also by telling them how they can do it and how they can reach you.

Sure. Great. I didn't know I was going to show the product. I thought we were just going to talk about ideology and so on. But yeah, probably your listeners heard something about this, but I'll just give a quick overview. You know, IVF has been around for 50 years. You basically stimulate the woman to produce eggs and you create embryos from that when you combine them with sperm. You can test those embryos for, you know, single gene disorders for about 30 years and for chromosomal abnormalities. This is called preimplantation genetic testing for aneuploidy in the case of chromosomes and for monogenic disorders in the case of single gene disorders. The interesting thing, and well, I'll just say first, what we're doing, the new thing, there are a few companies doing, is polygenic screening. And I'm friends with the founder of Genomic Prediction who did this first. And Steve Hsu, he's a trained physicist, but he's the first one to really offer in a business this way. He was a bit of a pioneer and maybe too early actually, because he got condemned probably more than we did seven or eight years ago. But also there wasn't that much you could do seven years ago You could reduce disease a bit some IQ prediction but it was pretty hard seven years ago Now given genome association studies the building of biobanks where huge numbers of people are genetically sequenced and matched up with their phenotype now we can, you know, generate pretty reasonably powerful polygenic scores for a variety of traits people care about. Type 1 diabetes, we have an extremely accurate predictor for that. Type 2 diabetes, less so, but still very strong. Schizophrenia, intelligence. And so basically what you can do now, if you're doing IVF and you have a range of embryos, a set of embryos, you can test them for these aneuploidy problems, most of which are incompatible with life. They would result in a miscarriage if you implanted the aneuploid embryo, monogenic, and now what we're doing, polygenic.

The reason I wanted to put all of that on the table is, yeah, it's true that we have the best polygenic predictors in the world, and you can read our papers. You can go to herasite.com and actually look at the technical analysis. We compare ourselves against different academic predictors and different private sector ones and so on. But here's the really interesting thing. So if you've done IVF, let's say in the last five years, or you're going to do it in the next five, what we don't need to do, and this is a real novelty, is we don't need to whole genome sequence your embryo directly. And that normally is the kind of thing you would need to do to make really good predictions about polygenic traits, right? Because intelligence, height, type 2 diabetes, it involves thousands and thousands of small genetic variants, not three or five. Sometimes there's a single gene that can affect it, but it's usually thousands and at least hundreds. So you'd better know, you'd better have a good picture of the whole genome to be able to run the DNA through a polygenic risk score to be able to predict these things. But we found a way around this and it's ingenious and it allows us to scale immediately around the world. So here's the way around it. When you do an aneuploidy test, that is the test for chromosomal abnormalities, it's offered at basically any clinic in the world, almost any clinic. Essentially, it's meant to count chromosomes, but what it actually does is if you request the raw genetic data, which even in Europe you have the right to do from this test, first of all, the doctor might be confused. Like, why do you want the genetic data from this test? You just wanted a PDF, didn't you, saying does it have Down syndrome or does it not? Well, what we can do with this extremely weak genetic data, it covers a tiny fraction of the genome is we can take that tiny fraction of the genome which is indicating something about where the where the blocks are which are coming from mom or dad, where sexual recombination is happening. We can take that data and then whole genome sequence the parents using both short and long read sequencing to really get a complete picture of the parents. And then we can algorithmically reconstruct the entire embryo genome with these two different sources of data, parental data plus this aneuploidy data that's available at any clinic. But it's still synthetic. It's not deterministic, right? It's synthetic in the sense that we're guessing at the whole genome. But here's the interesting thing. When you whole genome sequence an embryo directly, and Orchid is the first to do that. They're also a competitor and perfectly good company. But we can do that in our lab. But there are two things. One, we don't need to. It's extremely difficult and expensive, but actually we can prove that our reconstruction algorithm is actually better than whole genome sequencing directly. And how would we prove that actually? Because really, you know, you have a philosophy and econ background, right? And it's like, give me, give me the evidence. So here's the ultimate proof. And we've published it. You can look at it on our, on our website to prove that this works. And by the way, I should say, why is it's important. It unlocks this technology for everyone. You could be in Norway. You could be in Mongolia. Actually, I don't know about Norway. Check your local laws. But you could be in Mongolia. You could be in Dubai. You could be almost anywhere where this is legal. And you could take the aneuploidy test, request your raw genetic data. Then we send you spit kits and blood kits or whatever. It's really simple. And then we can basically serve you anywhere you are in the world without having a lab in your country or having any kind of operation. So that's the unlock. How do we know this works? First of all, we got a lot of feedback from the top academics in the field, but that's just social proof. So here's the ultimate test. We had a bunch of couples who had done IVF and aneuploidy testing, the PGTA test. They had had kids. And so we had to recruit these. We had to go through an IRB and all that stuff to recruit these people. And we asked them, we paid them whatever, some trivial amount, $200 or something to get them to do this. And we said, look can you please request your PGTA data from the test that you had a couple of years ago And then can we sequence you using short and long reads the parents And then what we going to do is we going to guess the entire whole genome of the born child that you had. And then after that, what we're going to do is sequence the kid, send them a spit kit, do that sort of thing. They swab the cheek. And then we're going to look at the concordance between the guessed genome and the actual genome. And it's as close as is necessary for for for polygenic prediction I don't want to get the numbers exactly wrong because I'm not involved on this part of the team it's something like 98 99 percent concordance it might even be might even be more yeah yeah that's probably like a very scientific and specific claim to make how concordant it is right exactly genetic overlap it gets you know the humans differ only in like several tens of thousands of genes and the whole gene is like several millions of strings so there's probably some very technical um debate there right yeah well we have like yeah and gene is gene is itself a a fraught term right usually it means something like protein coding region or whatever but we have six billion base pairs and we differ you know even if we only differ let's say in one percent of those that's that's actually millions and tens of millions right yeah of differences and so yeah what you want to do is really guess at that as accurately as possible but the interesting thing is although we also do monogenic testing and we do it really well we do double calling so we minimize false positive negatives you actually don't need to get the whole genome exactly 