# Summary

This episode explores the mechanisms by which overregulated institutions suppress genetic technologies while startup jurisdictions and market feedback loops enable their deployment, focusing on Jonathan Anomaly's shift from academic philosophy to co-founding Herasight for polygenic embryo screening via parental whole-genome sequencing plus low-coverage aneuploidy data reconstruction.

core concepts:

- Rational irrationality and preference falsification (Kuran) drive taboos; market prices discipline false beliefs faster than democratic aggregation.
- Algorithmic genome reconstruction bypasses direct embryo WGS, enabling global scaling of polygenic risk scoring for traits including disease liability, height, and intelligence.
- Early-adopter niches (pronatalists, Bay Area rationalists) generate credible testimonials that trigger preference cascades, turning private knowledge public without ideological marketing.
- Exit options (Prospera, crypto, tax reform) function analogously to defensive technologies by reducing capture risk and allowing simultaneous value creation for legacy jurisdictions.


